<h1>@HI{{wakedehanai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @EM{{@HI{{wakedehanai}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{wakedehanai}}}} is used to deny what is implied in the previous statement. It is often
used in cases where the circumstances may suggest one thing but the facts are different.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ikura@KJ{{day^book^word}}ga@KJ{{exit^come}}naito@KJ{{say}}ttemo@KJ{{whole^sort*of*thing^tale}}senai@EM{{wakedehanai}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Although I say I cannot speak Japanese, it does not mean I cannot speak it at all.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{wakedehanai}}}} is the negative form of <a href="grammar-wake-da.html">@HI{{wakeda}}</strong></a>.
</p>

